Here's the TikZ code that visualizes the sign propagation process:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning, arrows.meta}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    node distance=2cm,
    var/.style={circle, draw, minimum size=1cm, font=\bfseries},
    op/.style={above, sloped, font=\footnotesize},
    arrow/.style={-Stealth, thick}
]
    % Nodes
    \node[var] (v1) {$v_1$};
    \node[var, right=of v1] (v2) {$v_2$};
    \node[var, below=of v1] (v3) {$v_3$};

    % Edges with operations
    \draw[arrow] (v1) -- node[op] {$+\otimes +=+$} (v3);
    \draw[arrow] (v2) -- node[op] {$+\otimes -=-$} (v3);

    % Combination box
    \node[draw, dashed, rounded corners, fit=(v3), inner sep=0.5cm] (comb) {};
    \node[below=0.5cm of v3] (result) {$+\oplus -=?$};

    % Labels
    \node[above=0.2cm of v1] {$+$};
    \node[above=0.2cm of v2] {$+$};
    \node[below=0.2cm of v3] {$?$};

    % Annotations
    \draw[<-] (v1) -- ++(135:0.5cm) node[anchor=south east] {Parent};
    \draw[<-] (v2) -- ++(45:0.5cm) node[anchor=south west] {Parent};
    \draw[->] (comb.south) -- node[right] {Combined Result} (result);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code creates a diagram with:
1. Three circular nodes representing variables $v_1$, $v_2$, and $v_3$
2. Arrows showing sign propagation from parents to child
3. Operation labels on the arrows ($\otimes$ multiplication)
4. A dashed box around the combination process
5. The final sign combination ($\oplus$ addition) below
6. Parent/child annotations
7. Initial signs ($+$) above parents and final sign ($?$) below child

The diagram matches the described process where:
- Both parents ($v_1$ and $v_2$) have positive signs
- Each propagates a message through $\otimes$ operations
- The results are combined using $\oplus$ to produce the final "?" sign

